Singapore Stocks: Keppel, Sembcorp Marine, SingTel, Tiger Air

-- B y   J o n a t h a n   B u r g o s
-- 
2011-08-11T04:16:50Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-11/singapore-stocks-keppel-sembcorp-marine-singtel-tiger-air.html
Singapore’s  Straits Times Index (FSSTI) 
dropped 1.7 percent to 2,774.56 as of 12:08 p.m. local time,
headed for its lowest close since June 9. All stocks but two
stocks declined in the index of 30 companies.  Shares on the measure trade at an average 12.7 times
estimated earnings, compared with about 15.6 times at the end of
2010, according to data compiled by Bloomberg.  The following shares were among the most active in the
market. Stock symbols are in parentheses after the company name.  Oil-rig builders: Builders of platforms used in oil
exploration and production dropped as crude oil futures declined
in New York amid concern that the European sovereign debt crisis
is worsening.  Keppel Corp. (KEP SP), the world’s largest oil-rig builder,
sank 3.7 percent to S$8.86. Smaller Sembcorp Marine Ltd. (SMM SP)
decreased 4.9 percent to S$4.11.  Singapore Telecommunications Ltd. (ST)  , Southeast Asia’s
biggest phone company, declined 1.4 percent to S$2.91. SingTel,
as the company is known, said first-quarter net income fell 2.9
percent from a year earlier to S$916.2 million on lower earnings
from regional businesses such as India’s Bharti Airtel Ltd. That
compares with the S$991 million average estimate of three
analysts compiled by Bloomberg.  Tiger Airways Holdings Ltd. (TGR)  , the budget carrier
partly owned by Singapore Airlines Ltd. (SIA SP), slipped 2.4
percent to S$1.015. The company said it transported 358,000
passengers in July, 32 percent less than a year earlier, because
domestic flights in  Australia  were grounded. Regulators are
allowing services to resume tomorrow following suspension since
July 1 due to safety concerns.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Jonathan Burgos in  Singapore  at 
 jburgos4@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Nick Gentle at 
 ngentle2@bloomberg.net . 